This is a lab to explore transformations. The first part explores how to use the cdf to generate random draws for a continuous random variable. In this example, the transformation function is the cdf. The second part explores the transformation of a discrete random variable.

Generate a continuous random variable

  1. Suppose we are interested in simulating from a exponential distribution. This distribution will be discussed later in the course but an exponential distribution implies that \[ f\left(x\right) = \frac{1}{\beta} \exp\left\{\frac{-x}{\beta}\right\}\] where \(0<x<\infty\). Let \(\beta=1\).
    1. Find the cdf and inverse cdf
    2. Use the inverse cdf approach to obtain random draws from an exponential distribution. Compare the empirical density of your random draws to the true density. Compare the empirical cdf created from your random draws (use \(\textit{ecdf}\)) to the true cdf. You can use \(\textit{dexp}\) to get true density and \(\textit{pexp}\) to get true cdf.
    3. Compare the empirical denisty of random draws from b to the empirical density of random draws obtained using the \(\textit{rexp}\) function in R
    4. Check probability-integral transformation: Draw \(X\) from an Exp(1), computing \(Y=F(X)\), and show that \(Y\sim\text{UNIF(0,1)}\). Hint: You can check this by comparing the estimated pdfs and cdfs for Y to the pdfs and cdfs of a uniform distribution. Note \(\textit{dunif}\) finds the density of uniform distribution and \(\textit{punif}\) finds the cdf for a uniform distribution.

Solution for part a.

\[F\left(x\right) = \int_{0}^{x}\frac{1}{\beta}\exp\left\{-\frac{t}{\beta}\right\}dt= -\int_{0}^{x}-\frac{1}{\beta}\exp\left\{-\frac{t}{\beta}\right\}dt=-e^{-\frac{t}{\beta}}\Big\rvert_{0}^{x}=-\left[\exp\left\{{-\frac{x}{\beta}}\right\}- \exp\left\{0\right\}\right]=1-\exp\left\{-\frac{x}{\beta}\right\}\] \[y = 1-e^{-\frac{x}{\beta}}\] \[y-1=-e^{-\frac{x}{\beta}}\]

\[1-y = e^{-\frac{x}{\beta}}\] \[\log\left(1-y\right)=-\frac{x}{\beta}\] \[x=\beta \log \left(1-y\right)\] \[g^{-1}\left(y\right) = \beta \log \left(1-y\right)\]

Solution for b

Use inverse of cdf

seed = 123
set.seed(seed)
n<-1000
beta.val = 1
f.inv = function(x,beta.val){-beta.val*log(1-x)}
y = runif(n)  ## generates n random draws from the interval (0,1)
X.exp = f.inv(y,beta.val =1)

Compare empirical density to true density using the dexp function in R

 ## empirical density
hist(X.exp,freq=FALSE, main  = "Density vs Truth")    ## empirical density

## true density
t<-seq(0,10,by = 0.01)
lines(t,dexp(t,1/beta.val),col = "red")

Compare the empirical cdf to the true cdf

plot(ecdf(X.exp),main = "rexp, Empirical cdf vs truth")  ## empirical cdf using ecdf function
lines(t,pexp(t,1/beta.val),col=2)    ## true cdf using pexp function

Solution for c

X2.exp = rexp(n = n, rate = 1/beta.val)  ## random draws using R instead of inverse cdf
hist(X.exp, col=rgb(1,0,0,0.5),xlim=c(min(c(X.exp,X2.exp)),max(c(X.exp,X2.exp))), 
     main="Part c")
hist(X2.exp, col=rgb(0,0,1,0.5),add=T)

Solution for d

## simulate values and plot pdf (histogram) and cdf here.

# Generate Exp(1) data
data <- rexp(1e4)

# Transform using CDF
transformed <- 1 - exp(-1*data)

# Plot the data -- should be uniform
hist(transformed)

# Plot uniform data for comparison
hist(runif(1e4))

# Compare CDFs
grid <- seq(0,1,0.01)
plot(ecdf(transformed))  ## empirical cdf using ecdf function
lines(grid, punif(grid),col=2) # true cdf using pexp function

Estimate the pmf for a transformed discrete random variable

  1. Let X be the value shown when you roll a six sided die and \(Y = (X-2)^2\). Find \(f_Y\left(y\right)\) via simulation and compare to true density values.

Simulation code

## ++++++++++++++++
## simulation parameters
## ++++++++++++++++
num.sims<-10000
seed.use <- 124
set.seed(seed.use)

rolls <- purrr::map_dbl(1:num.sims, ~sample(1:6, size=1))
transformed_rolls <- (rolls-2)^2

p <- table(transformed_rolls) %>% as.numeric() /num.sims
Y P(Y=y) True pmf
